metadata.name: Floatrest #256
metadata.description:
Floating forests over the endless sky, where birds, trees, plants, roots, rocks and waterfalls share an ecosystem full of life and emotion.

You can see some rain clouds in the sky and the sun shining under the raindrops.

The earth is moving, the blocks are falling, but the trees are strong in their roots.

Welcome to 'Floatrest'.

----

# Features

- 7 tree palettes
- 17 different background colors
- 10 different terrain colors
- clouds
- vines
- roots
- plants
- waterfall
- birds
- sun / moon
- night
- dark mode
- monochromatic
- 2 different aspect ratios (square & portrait)
- Press "p" on live mode to save in PNG

This artwork requires processing power and is intended for laptops and desktops primarily. It may take some time to render.

----

July 2022, gpitombo

metadata.name: KONSTRUKTS #97
metadata.description:
A study of building and destroying. I built this. You may knock it over.

Humans are both creators and destroyers. One of the earliest games children learn to play is building with blocks, then knocking them down. This simple activity is teaching kids about gravity, cause and effect, and imposing their will on the world around them. As children grow older, the gap between these opposing actions widens. The intention behind knocking things down becomes less innocent, and creators aren't as excited to see their work destroyed.

In 1915, the Russian avant-garde founded the abstract art movement known as Constructivism, rejecting everything except for the absolute purest aspects of form and material. This art was used in service of the Russian revolution and utilized heavily in its propaganda, intended to highlight the utilitarian nature of industrial progress. Mainly, building the new Russia. Its influence is lasting, and can be seen throughout art and design trends even today.

When Russia invaded Ukraine in February of 2022, footage of missiles and airstrikes decimating Ukrainian buildings permeated the media. Ukrainian lives, kitchens, windowsill gardens, and family photos tumbled to the ground. Like children's blocks. Things that took a lifetime to build were destroyed in seconds. 

KONSTRUKTS represents this duality in creation and destruction. Stacked children's blocks are rendered in the style of Constructivist designs like El Lissitzky's Proun series, and Alexander Rodchenko's posters. With a simple tap, blocks (or buildings) can be knocked to the ground.

- Tap anywhere to reveal the KONSTRUKTS menu in the top left. Tap the menu for several options.
- KONSTRUKTS can be exported as USDZ or GLTF models to be used in augmented reality or the metaverse.
- Export a full resolution PNG image from the menu.
- If you knocked over the blocks, you can reset them from the menu.

KONSTRUKTS is built entirely with code, using Three.js, JavaScript, and GLSL.

metadata.name: Memory Module #41
metadata.description:
Day by day, memories accumulate and shape our dreams, subconscious, ideals, and ultimately, the innermost self. 

This artwork is created by repeatedly drawing squares that are identical in size, with each one representing a memory. As new memories form, the older ones become obscured, fuzzy, or joined with others to form belief structures and intuitions. I hope that this work will remind you of someone, someplace, a song or a melody that’s important to you. 

Keyboard controls:
[S] Save the current view in live mode.
[1] to [8] Change resolution, 1.5K to 12K.
[G] Toggle paper texture.

URL params:
aspect: custom aspect ratio (?aspect=3).
res: custom resolution multiplier (?res=4).

Made with fractal math and p5js, Memory Module is the first in a 5-part generative art series about introspection. You can read more about the series here: https://elsifthen.github.io/

Created by elsif, 2022.07.

metadata.name: twofiftythousand #58
metadata.description:
twofiftythousand is about the chaos of unlimited decisions. Look for a pattern in the noise.

Press 's' to save an image while in full-screen mode.

If you want to increase the resolution of the saved image, add e.g. &size=2000 after the live/fullscreen view URL to render the canvas at that specific pixel width (default = browser sized). This will be dependent on your system specifications, but outputs of up to 8000px wide, or above, should be possible.

metadata.name: The Living Book #1 #26
metadata.description:
I have been exploring the medium of print for years. Mixing etching, silk-screening, offset, photocopy, risography, drawing and painting to design and craft experimental art books.From the day digital, which had always fascinated me, took over my publishing practice, I always liked to create bridges between these two worlds.

The Living Books is part of this series of hybrid and experimental works where paper and digital resonate.

This issue #1 is made of 64 pages that will be minted by collectors. A book will eventually be printed and the pages will follow the mint order. Each page exists in a cover version (c) and a xerox version (x).

Controls :

• Click to dive into each frame.
• Press C to toggle cover mode.
• Press X to toggle xerox mode.
• Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

———————

The Living Book #1 by Ferdinand Dervieux, 2022
Made with Unity

metadata.name: Miniscapes #340
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

We hope that you find as much joy in owning a Miniscape as we did in creating them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [p] to pause an animated output
- Press [r] to reset an animated output (this will also pause)

metadata.name: sunz #7
metadata.description:
Your spaceship enters a wormhole and emerges in a distant solar system. The crew is surprised to find that the star system is full of metal plates, which may be the remains of a long-destroyed civilization. They soon realize that they are in an alien shipyard. The crew must find a way to escape before the aliens find them.

This NFT has 5 features with unique distributions:

"debris chunks": do the metal plates form chunks of shapes?
"density": how many metal plates occur?
"mirror": are the plates arranged in a mirrored fashion?
"sun size": how big is the sun you are facing?
"speed": how quick is the spaceship flying?

In addition, there are a lot of unique traits that have not been exposed as a feature, but still contribute to the overall scene and provide a distinctive style. For example each scene has it's own soundscape of composed ambient drones. Another one is a special color grading technique that is selected.

Some infos:
- click the canvas or press h/i to get an info window (including FPS)
- press "S" to toggle a mysterious samples setting
- press "C" to toggle the chromatic abberation effect
- press "M" to toggle music
- press "+" to increase PPI for screenshots
- press "space" to take screenshots (PPI * current viewport)

You need a good computer and a modern browser like Chrome to run this simulation with decent FPS.

metadata.name: Variations #9
metadata.description:
Thousands of rectangles of 8 different colors are positioned on the screen, each color following its own pattern.

By doing so they form shapes that are similar in some aspects, different in others, and together create a larger pattern. Sometimes these shapes are grouped to form another pattern at an intermediate level.

Each iteration, once minted, will also become part of a larger whole that is the generative piece.

SVG generated with JavaScript.

The SVG can be saved by pressing "s" on the full-screen view.
A PNG version can be exported by pressing "e" on the full-screen view.

By default the dimensions of the export are 3200×3200.
These dimensions can be changed by adding, for example, ?w=5000 to the full-screen page URL, where w is the desired width. Then press "e" to export at this size.

objkt.name: Julia's Magical Bulbs - The Second Power #65

metadata.name: Julia's Magical Bulbs - The Second Power #65
metadata.description:
Julia's Magical Bulbs are 3D dimensional fractals, based on the Julia Sets of the Mandelbulb fractal.

The token is interactive, use your mouse-wheel to zoom-in and see all the little details. You will find a menu in the lower-right corner which allows you to play with the iterations and camera position. You can also render high-resolution images here.

A little bit of magic happens when you select low iteration values, perhaps your token will even default to this. 

Technical:

Not all browsers support multi-threaded modules, the fallback mode is quite slow. Try Chrome if your browser is not supported.

Calculated in full 64-bit on the CPU (not the GPU) for more accurate and detailed images.

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #279
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. “The Bugged Tree”’s code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren’t under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there’s a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: Shape Study  #121
metadata.description:
“Everyone has their own shape.”
We meet shapes of all kinds in our life.

Algorithmic randomness generates shapes ever so slightly different yet similar. 
I suppose these are someone’s collection.

“Why do they need to have so many similar things?”

Perhaps it’s their versatility in the pleasure they could bring.
Perhaps they’re meant for different occasions.
Perhaps some are left to search for their very own shapes.

Seeing this, I realized that when people explore themselves or others, it is also a form of shape study.
With what’s visible and concrete, explore the unseen and abstract.

However, good shapes only come by chance.
Shapes, in truth, cannot be good or bad in and of themselves. It’s only when two shapes come together that the meaning thereof arises.
I hope you who decide to pick up this work will find the shapes to your liking.

『每個人都有自己的形狀』
並且每個人一生中也會認識各種形狀

程式的隨機性讓我產生的每個形狀都相似而不同
我想像這也許是某個人的蒐藏
『為什麼會需要擁有這麼多相似的道具呢？』

也許是它們有著不同的功能，能帶來不同的愉悅；
也許是適用於不同的場景
也許是遲遲未找到屬於自己的形狀

想像至此，我意識到：當人們探索自己／他人的同時，也可以說是一種形狀研究
用一個看得見的具體，去探索一個看不見的抽象

然而，好的形狀是可遇不可求的
其實形狀本身沒有好壞，只有當兩個形狀相遇時，形狀才有了意義
希望蒐藏這件作品的各位都可以遇到喜歡的形狀

metadata.name: Ongemak #54
metadata.description:
Wabi-sabi (侘寂): appreciate impermanence and imperfection

There is little chance of a 'perfect' work of art. The small imperfections require reflection. 

The variation and randomness give the work some asymmetry, common in wabi-sabi esthetics. Because of a limited color palette and the simple shapes used, the works keep their simplicity (another principle of wabi-sabi). The noisy texture gives it some roughness, indeed again a core principle of wabi-sabi. 

The colors are reminiscent of the 70s and 80s. Some think that everything was better in the past. The trick is to enjoy the moment.

Thinking about impermanence is sometimes uncomfortable, 'ongemak' in Dutch, but also valuable.

metadata.name: Penumbra #60
metadata.description:
Penumbra is a geometric exploration of the possible outcomes from 3 basic rules:

1) Place some walls
2) Place some light sources
3) Draw the resulting shadows

This series is a small thank you to the collectors of Umbra :)

metadata.name: Ersbla #491
metadata.description:
Ersbla is part of the fxhash live minting experience at Proof of People, London 2022. 

It is the third entry in a series of abstract generative experiments inspired by the graphic and textile work of Anni and Josef Albers. As a follow-up to the 'Sabler' and 'Lebras' collections, 'Ersbla' produces textile effects using a combination of thousands of tiny dots arranged on variable grids, resulting in a wide variety of unique Bauhaus-inspired compositions in a variety of palettes.

Press 'S' to save a high-resolution 2400 x 3396 px image in PNG format.

Depending on the density of your output, please allow up to a few seconds for your edition to generate.
